<main class="main"><div id="content" class="pretext-content"><section class="section" id="section-2"><h2 class="heading hide-type">
<span class="type">Section</span> <span class="codenumber">1.2</span> <span class="title">Rules for Integration</span>
</h2>
<p id="p-16">Just as Differential Calculus is literally the rules for (infinitely small) differences, Integral Calculus is the rules for summing up these differences.  Not surprisingly, each differentiation rule has its integration rule counterpart.  The following table illustrates some of these rules.</p>
<figure class="table table-like" id="BasicIntegrationTable"><figcaption><span class="type">Table</span><span class="space"> </span><span class="codenumber">1.1<span class="period">.</span></span><span class="space"> </span>Inherited Integration Rules</figcaption><div class="tabular-box natural-width"><table class="tabular">
<tr class="header-horizontal">
<th scope="col" class="l m b3 r0 l0 t0 lines">Differentiation Rule</th>
<th scope="col" class="l m b3 r0 l0 t0 lines">Integration Rule<br>(Assume <span class="process-math">\(a\)</span> and <span class="process-math">\(c\)</span> are constants.)</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\text{constant})=0\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines">
<span class="process-math">\(\int0\dx{x}=c,\)</span><br>where <span class="process-math">\(c \)</span> is a constant.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(f+g)=\dx{f}+\dx{g}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int\dx(f+g)
=\int\dx{f}+\int\dx{g}=f+g+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines">If <span class="process-math">\(a\)</span> is a constant, then<br><span class="process-math">\(\dx(ay)=a\dx(y)\)</span>
</td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int a\dx{y}=\int\dx(ay)=a\int\dx{y}=ay+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(x^{n+1})=(n+1)x^n\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int x^n\dx{x} = \frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1}+c, n\neq -1\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\ln(x))=\frac1x\dx{x}=x^{-1}\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int x^{-1}\dx{x} = \ln\abs{x}+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(e^x)= e^x\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int e^x\dx{x} = e^x+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\sin(x))=\cos(x)\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int \cos(x) = \sin(x) +c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\cos(x))=-\sin(x)\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int \sin(x)\dx{x} = -\cos(x) +c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\tan(x))=\sec^2(x)\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int\sec^2(x)\dx{x} = \tan(x)+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\sec(x))= \sec(x)\tan(x)\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int\sec(x)\tan(x)=\sec(x)+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\inverse\sin(x))= \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\inverse\tan(x))= \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\dx(\inverse\sec(x))= \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}\)</span></td>
<td class="l m b0 r0 l0 t0 lines"><span class="process-math">\(\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+c\)</span></td>
</tr>
</table></div></figure><p id="p-17"><a href="" class="xref" data-knowl="./knowl/BasicIntegrationTable.html" title="Table 1.1: Inherited Integration Rules">Table 1.1</a> is not exhaustive, as every differentiation performed gives rise to a corresponding integration formula.  Conspicuously absent are the product rule, quotient rule, and chain rule.  The analog of the quotient rule is rather limited in its applicability and typically is not used.  The analogs of the others are quite useful and will be covered later.  Notice that the analog of the power rule  (line 4) makes sense verbally.  To differentiate <span class="process-math">\(x\)</span>  to a power, you multiply by the exponent and then subtract one from the exponent.  To reverse the process, you reverse each step and reverse the order of the steps (much as you put your socks on and then your shoes and to reverse it you take off your shoes first and then your socks).  Thus you add one to the exponent and then divide by the exponent.  Notice that the rule will not work if the exponent is <span class="process-math">\(n=-1\)</span> as you cannot divide by zero.  This is where the natural logarithm fills in the gap (line 5).  While we are at line five, notice that we have inserted an absolute value in the formula:</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="./knowl/BasicIntegrationTable.html">
\begin{equation*}
\int\inverse x\dx{x}=\ln\abs{x}+C.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<article class="problem example-like" id="problem-1"><a href="" data-knowl="" class="id-ref problem-knowl original" data-refid="hk-problem-1"><h3 class="heading">
<span class="type">Drill</span><span class="space"> </span><span class="codenumber">1.2</span><span class="period">.</span>
</h3></a></article><div class="hidden-content tex2jax_ignore" id="hk-problem-1"><article class="problem example-like"><p id="p-18">One way to define the absolute value function is <span class="process-math">\(\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}\)</span> where his signifies the non-negative square root.  For example, <span class="process-math">\(\abs{3}=\sqrt(3^2)=\sqrt(9)=3\)</span> and <span class="process-math">\(\abs{-3}=\sqrt{(-3)^2}=\sqrt{9}=3\text{.}\)</span></p>
<p id="p-19">Show that with this definition of absolute value, we still obtain the formula</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\dx(\ln\abs{x})=\frac1x \dx{x}.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class="solutions">
<a href="" data-knowl="" class="id-ref hint-knowl original" data-refid="hk-hint-1" id="hint-1"><span class="type">Hint</span><span class="period">.</span></a><div class="hidden-content tex2jax_ignore" id="hk-hint-1"><div class="hint solution-like"><p id="p-20">Be careful that you do not try to take the logarithm of a negative number. A common practice is to write <span class="process-math">\(\int\inverse
x\dx{x}=\ln(x)+C\text{,}\)</span> even though this is only valid for .  We will adopt this practice, and resort to an absolute value only when there is an issue about being negative.</p></div></div>
</div></article></div>
<article class="problem example-like" id="problem-2"><a href="" data-knowl="" class="id-ref problem-knowl original" data-refid="hk-problem-2"><h3 class="heading">
<span class="type">Drill</span><span class="space"> </span><span class="codenumber">1.3</span><span class="period">.</span>
</h3></a></article><div class="hidden-content tex2jax_ignore" id="hk-problem-2"><article class="problem example-like"><p id="p-21">It looks like we broke our own rule in lines two and three in the above table of integration rules.  After all,</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int \dx{f} +\int \dx{g} = f+c_1+g+c_2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">where  and  are arbitrary constants, and</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
a\int\dx{y}=a(y+c)=ay+ac\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id="p-22">Explain why what we have in the table is still legitimate.</p></article></div>
<p id="p-23">In light of the above problem, practitioners often will perform the integration of a differential applying whatever tools are appropriate and then combining any arbitrary constants into one constant at the end.  For example, consider</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="" id="md-1">
\begin{align*}
\int\left(5x^2-3\sqrt{x}+\frac{2}{1+x^2}\right)\dx{x}\amp=5\int
x^2\dx{x}-3\int x^\frac12 \dx{x}+2\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}\\
\amp=5\left(\frac{x^3}{3}\right) -
\frac{3\left(x^{\frac12}\right)}{\frac32} + 2\inverse\tan(x)+c\\
\amp=\frac53x^3-2x^{\frac32}+2\inverse\tan(x)+c.
\end{align*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">As with differentiation rules, when you get more comfortable with the integration rules, you will probably do these in your head.  Again, developing this fluency this is why you need to practice.</p>
<article class="question example-like" id="question-1"><a href="" data-knowl="" class="id-ref question-knowl original" data-refid="hk-question-1"><h3 class="heading">
<span class="type">Question</span><span class="space"> </span><span class="codenumber">1.4</span><span class="period">.</span>
</h3></a></article><div class="hidden-content tex2jax_ignore" id="hk-question-1"><article class="question example-like"><p id="p-24">question goes here</p></article></div>
<p id="p-25">We have made a good start, but we are still a bit away from solving differential equations such as</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\dfdxn{y}{x}{2} = \frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2}.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">A start might be to let <span class="process-math">\(z=\dfdx{y}{x}\text{,}\)</span> so we have</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="" id="md-2">
\begin{align*}
\dfdx{z}{x}\amp=\frac{w}{H}\sqrt{1+z^2}\\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}\amp=\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}.
\end{align*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">If we now integrate both sides we get</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\int\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id="p-26">The right-hand side of this doesn’t pose any problems since <span class="process-math">\(\frac{w}{H}\)</span> is a constant.  However, the left-hand side is another matter, since it doesn’t quite fit with anything in our table. We will learn techniques to handle such situations, but first let’s look at some applications of integration which utilize what we know.</p></section></div></main>
</div>
</body>
</html>
